data.name: tao-nomiss
data.description: It contains some records taken from the Tropical Ocean Atmosphere project, http://www.pmel.noaa.gov/tao/. This project maintains a grid of buoys in the Pacific Ocean that provide an early warning system to detect El Nino and La Nina events. The subset that is available here contains measurements on sea surface temperature (SST), air temperature (AirT), relative humidity (Hum), east-west component of wind (UWind), and north-south component of wind (VWind). They are the daily average values for 2 time periods Nov 1, 1993-Jan 31, 1994, and Nov 1, 1997-Jan 31, 1998. The former was considered to be a normal season, the latter a very extreme El Nino event occurred in the time period. There are several different buoys included, and the location of these is defined by the Latitude and Longitude positions. The buoys differ slightly for each time period because the available data by buoy differed some.
